1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Nb6
{ Almost universally played as the alternatives are questionable. } 6. Nf3 Nc6
7. O-O Be7 8. Rb1
{ This is a tricky move that sets Black some problems without risking anything at all. Play might become very sharp, but White might still return to more restrained play if he desires to do so. }
8... O-O 9. b4 { The point of Rb1. } 9... f6 10. b5 Nd4 11. a4
{ Very quick progress on the queenside ! } 11... a5 12. e3 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3
{ Here White is better. Let's check some moves to get a feel for the play. }
13... Bf5 14. Qb3+ Kh8 15. Bxb7
{ An easy decision. White has great play for the exchange. } 15... Bxb1 16.
Qxb1 Rb8 17. Be4 g6 18. Bb2 Bb4 19. Rd1
{ This is much more comfortable for White. He's got a pawn, better structure and the pair of Bishops for the exchange. }
