[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 f5
{ The Reversed Grand Prix Attack. Other options in this position are mostly just transpositional. }
4. Nc3 Nf6 5. e3 g6
{ This is one of the better options for Black, getting back to the setup of a Closed Reversed Sicilian. White is commited to e3 here, but this is a good setup anyway. A sample line: }
6. Nge2 Bg7 7. d3 O-O 8. O-O d6 9. Rb1
{ with a position type we are familiar with. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 c4 e5 2 g3 Nc6 3 Bg2 g6"]
[Black "1 c4 e5 2 g3 Nc6 3 Bg2 g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6
{ The Reversed Closed Sicilian. This is a quite solid option for Black against the English Opening. However it is well established that Black has no problems whatsoever in the Closed Sicilian after 1 e4 c5 2 Nc3 and an extra tempo is quite helpful for the queenside play, leading to a comfortable situation for White. }
4. Nc3 Bg7 { +=4 } 5. e4
{ , leading to different position types. In particular the Botvinnik setup with e4 leads to positions where White has very good control and chances for a small edge.All those lines are playable with little knowledge of concrete moves. If you study lots of games with these structures you will be able to vary your play and make your game more flexible. }
*

