[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 c4 e5 2 g3 Nc6 3 Bg2 g6"]
[Black "1 c4 e5 2 g3 Nc6 3 Bg2 g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6
{ The Reversed Closed Sicilian. This is a quite solid option for Black against the English Opening. However it is well established that Black has no problems whatsoever in the Closed Sicilian after 1 e4 c5 2 Nc3 and an extra tempo is quite helpful for the queenside play, leading to a comfortable situation for White. }
4. Nc3 Bg7 5. Rb1
{ I suggest this line, going for a quick b4. White has some options here in fact. Other lines that I like are }
5... a5 { Making sure that the a-file is opened after a later b4. } 6. a3 d6 7.
b4 axb4 8. axb4 f5 { is also possible of course. } 9. b5 Nce7 { +=4 } 10. d3
Nf6 11. Nf3 O-O 12. O-O h6
{ is also very much possible. In fact there are move orders that lead into this position that are hard to avoid as you don't get e3/Nge2 played - see the 1 c4 e5 2 g3 d6 move order of Chapter 3 for an example of this. So we should have a look how it might continue. }
13. Bb2 Be6 14. Ra1 Qd7 15. Nd2 c6 16. Qc2 Kh7 17. Na4
{ and White was slightly better in Ivanchuk,V  (2726)  -Vitiugov,N  (2725)  Berlin 2015. It is very much recommended to study this position type by going through as many master games as possible. Learning moves by heart does not help here, learning the middlegame ideas does. }
*

