1. c4 c5
{ The Symmetrical English. Quite often 'Symmetrical' in Chess signals that the play is on the solid or even boring side if both players don't want to spice it up. In our case White has a fundamental decision to make right on move 2. }
2. g3 { The main alternative is } 2... Nf6 3. Bg2 { and now } 3... d5
{ sees Black trying to grab the initiative in the center. It leads to interesting play and is covered in Chapter 10. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 c4 c5 Intro and Ideas"]
[Black "1 c4 c5 Intro and Ideas"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5 { +=4 } 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ This is the big alternative with the idea to play for d2-d4 very soon, most often right on move 3 or 4. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ with an open, far more concrete play. I decided against this for the repertoire presented here, mostly for two reasons. 1. It is very complex, so it would have required far too much coverage. 2. There are many move order issues, the most serious being Nf6 and g6. which need to be addressed in a much more sophisticated way as well. We play the English in a more 'setup' approach - the Nf3/d4 Symmetrical is the 'move-by-move' approach to test Black's concrete knowledge of lines... meaning that we also have to know much more concrete lines. }
*

