{ is probably the main line. The nonforced nature of the play gives Black many more options of course. }
6. Rb1 Nge7 7. b4 d6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O b6 10. e3 Bb7 11. Qb3 Qd7 12. Bb2 Rac8
13. d3
{ This is probably about equal, but as written above already: there are no trades and all pieces are on the board. Here the real battle is delayed until a later stage of the game. Possible White plans here include to try to play d3-d4  (Rfd1 comes to mind)  or try to trade the dark squared Bishops. }
