[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6
{ The Knight clearly belongs to c6 here, but of course Black might start with }
5. a3 { Now } 5... e5
{ The Botvinnik setup is a solid as it gets, just not a good choice in this particular position. }
6. b4 d6
{ This is still quite playable for Black, but White enjoys a good game. He has managed b4 quickly and still has the option to go e3 and Nge2  (compare with 5 Nf3 e5 for example)  . We now have a look at a classic game from this position. }
7. Rb1 Nge7 8. e3 O-O 9. d3 Rb8 10. Nge2 Be6 11. b5 Na5 12. Bd2 b6 13. O-O Nb7
14. e4
{ Blocking the centre, but White has more space and the Black Knight on b7 is not a happy camper. }
14... Kh8 15. Qc1 f5 16. Bg5 Qe8 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. exf5 Bxf5 19. Nd5 Qd7 20.
Qd2 Na5 21. Nec3 Rbe8 22. Ne4
{ This was Kasparov,G  (2740)  -Karpov,A  (2700)  Seville 1987. Yes, somehow Karpov stumbled into this line in a World Championship Match ! Black is worse, being annoyed by white's Knights and his own piece on a5 offside. }
