1. c4 c6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. b3
{ I like this double fianchetto, but White has other ideas as well. } 5... Bg7
6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O
{ At this point Black has played about every move that doesn't lose material. I will show some examples for the most popular ones. This whole system does not look all too dangerous for Black, but White has a small edge everywhere. The main reason is that White has more ideas regarding possible pawn structure changes. He may play on the Queenside with a later b4, or go for d3/e4 in the centre. White also quite frequently gets the Bishop pair because the c8 Bishop is often traded on f3 for lack of a better job. }
7... b6 { +=4 } 8. d3
{ This is also possible, but Black signaling the will to put the Bishop on b7 encourages to play more actively in the centre - so I prefer d4 instead. }
*

