3... Nf6 { , but Black has some alternatives. } 4. Nf3 dxc4
{ The most critical move here. } 5. Qa4+
{ no fancy stuff - let's get the pawn back. } 5... Nbd7
{ This is the most popular move, but the alternatives are very viable and need to be checked carefully. }
6. Qxc4 c5 7. Qb3 Rb8 8. a4 b6 { Important. Black is in time to prevent a5. }
9. d3 Bd6 10. Na3 a6 11. Nc4 Bc7 12. Bd2 Bb7 13. O-O O-O
{ Black played very precisely to reach this position. White is still a bit easier to play though. Some examples: }
14. e4 b5 15. axb5 axb5 16. Na5 Ba8 17. Qa3 Bb6 18. b4
{ This complicated position is roughly equal. Black's play is very solid in this line,given that he is very precise. White retains chances for an edge if Black slips  (which happens quite often)  , otherwise it will be a full board of pieces with complicated play. }
