[Black "1 c4 e6 g3 d5 3 Bg2 Nf6 4 Nf3 Be7 12"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7
{ The most classical setup, usually signaling that Black is aiming to defend the Catalan main line. }
5. O-O O-O 6. b3 c5
{ A principled reaction, putting the c-pawn into the game. Black has a number of alternatives though. }
7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bb2 Nc6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Rc8 13.
Rc1 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Bf6 15. Qd3 Bxc3 16. Rxc3 Rxc3 17. Qxc3 Qb6 18. Rc1 h6 19.
Qe5 Bc6 { This was based on a miscalculation. } 20. Bxc6 Rc8 21. Rc4 bxc6 22.
Rg4 g5 23. Qf6 Qd8 24. Qxh6 f6 25. h4
{ This was the Van Kampen,R  (2615)  -Wojtaszek,R  (2741)  Germany 2016. To sum it up: this complex of the Reti is a low risk approach for White. He has chances for an edge, but risks little in the process. A good alternative is the Catalan with 6 d4. }
