1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7
{ The most classical setup, usually signaling that Black is aiming to defend the Catalan main line. }
5. O-O O-O 6. b3 c5
{ A principled reaction, putting the c-pawn into the game. Black has a number of alternatives though. }
7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bb2 Nc6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bf6 12. Qd2 Bd7
{ +=4 } 13. Bxd5 exd5
{ This leads to a position that White will never ever lose, but probably also never wins if Black plays correctly. }
14. Rd1 Rc8 15. Nc3 Bc6 16. Nxd5 Bxb2 17. Qxb2 Bxd5 18. e4 Bxe4 19. Rxd8 Rfxd8
{ This very logical sequence was played in Kramnik,V  (2783)  -Nakamura,H  (2776)  Zuerich 2015. White has basically no chances to break this fortress. }
