1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7
{ The most classical setup, usually signaling that Black is aiming to defend the Catalan main line. }
5. O-O O-O 6. b3 d4
{ Grabbing space in the centre and going for a reversed Benoni position. } 7.
e3
{ It is important that White has not yet played Bb2. The bishop is misplaced once a pawn comes to d4, so I will avoid this scenario during this repertoire. }
7... c5 8. exd4 cxd4 9. Re1 Nc6 10. d3
{ A good moment to take stock. It is a reversed Modern Benoni where Black's setup is not very testing, at least he is ages away from a central pawn roller or any other concrete threats. White has played the not very essential move b3, but this actually can be used in some cases to good effect. A key thing to remember is that trading one or better even two pairs of minor pieces favors White, as he has less space. In particular the c1 bishop is completely useless in most cases. }
10... Nd7 11. Na3 e5 12. Nc2 a5 13. a3
{ Note that b3 proved to be useful here, as otherwise Black would have had .. .a4. }
13... f6 14. Rb1 Nc5 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 Na4 17. Bd2 Bf5 18. b5 Nb8 19. Nfxd4
{ A very nice shot ! } 19... exd4 20. Bxb7 Ra7 21. Bd5+ Kh8 22. Nxd4 Bxd3 23.
Ne6 Qc8 24. Ra1 Bxc4 25. Qg4 Bb4 26. Bxb4 Bxd5 27. Bxf8 Bxe6 28. Rxe6
{ 1-0  (28)  Nikolic,P  (2623)  -Szabo,K  (2508)  Budva 2009. A very nice display of White's chances in this line. }
