1. c4 { This Chapter deals with the Fianchettos 1..g6 and b6. } 1... b6 2. e4
Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 { By far the most common. } 4. Nge2
{ Quite a sophisticated move. White wants to play with g3 later, but avoids 4 g3 f5 !, which is OK for black. }
4... Nf6 5. d3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. e5 Nfd7 8. d4 c5 9. f4 Nc6 10. Be3
{ This position is quite unusual for our repertoire. The good news is: White is just better ! }
10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bc5 13. Be2 { This seems best here. } 13...
O-O 14. O-O
{ White has the better structure here and Black's B on b7 is miserable. Some more moves to illustrate: }
14... Qe7 15. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 16. Rf2 Rad8 17. Nb5 Qe7 18. Nd6
{ and White can be very happy here. } *

