[Result "*"]

1. c4 f5
{ Going Dutch ! Not something we need to be particularly afraid of, but it helps to check out some details. In fact Black has 3 main setups of choose from. 1. The Stonewall with e6/d5 and c6 most of the time. 2. The Leningrad with g6, d6 and 3. The Classical with e6, Be7, d6. We are very happy about the Stonewall, as not having played d4 yet is helpful for White. We'll get an edge here and sometimes even a lot more if Black is imprecise. The Leningrad setup will most likely just transpose into 1 c4 e5 territory, as we go for the standard setup with g3 and a later Rb1 and Black playing d6/e5 is very natural. Against the Classical I recommend to actually go d4 and transpose to the mainline Dutch. White seems to be comfortable here and the alternatives to stay within English Opening territory didn't convince me. Let's check details ! }
2. g3
{ Consistent, but there is a nice offbeat alternative that I want to present briefly. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 { So Black wants to go for a Stonewall or Classical Dutch. }
4. Nf3 Be7 { Still being flexible with the d-pawn. } 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 d6
{ The Classical Dutch setup. } 7. d4
{ I suggest to just go into a main line Dutch here. There is little point in allowing black to play ...e5 if we can prevent that and be better with little effort. }
7... Ne4 8. Bb2 Bf6 9. Nbd2 Nc6 10. Ne1
{ This is a key move. White is just better now - at least I don't see how Black gets normal play. This Ne1 also should be considered if Black plays other things than Nc6/Bf6, which however is very natural. }
10... Nc5
{ This move was recommended by GM Simon Williams in his book "The Killer Dutch", but I think White is better in more than one way. }
11. e3 a5 12. f4 Na6 13. a3 d5 14. Nd3 b6 15. b4
{ This was played in Moradiabadi,E  (2570)  -Horvath,J  (2538)  Vaujany 2015. Black's position is already falling apart. }
*

