1. c4
{ Now we get to the point where some really obscure lines are left to check. In fact you may argue that they don't NEED to be checked, but I still like to have a look and have some fun dismantling bad play. }
1... Nc6
{ Developing the Knight so It can't be that bad for Black. One option is 2 d4 now, which will transpose to 1 d4 style play where White has good chances for a plus  (Chigorin, Tango etc)  . However staying within the English Opening is possible as well. }
2. Nc3 e5 3. g3 Bb4
{ We don't get this position from 1 c4 e5, as we play 2 g3 and 3 Bg2, so there is no Knight to pseudo-pin. Not a big deal though, play is normal enough - so in the rare cases you might get it from Nc6 you won't be out of your comfort zone. Some more moves: }
4. Nd5 Bc5 5. Bg2 Nf6 6. e3
{ I think White is slightly better here. As mentioned I wouldn't worry too much about this obscure move order. Checking some games from this position however does not hurt of course - can never have too much middlegame study in the English ! }
*

